\pard\plain \ri-17683\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A (modelling) language is used to convey *distinctions*. The predominant purpose of modelling is to describe (a domain in) reality by distinguishing the entities of interest. The distinctions that are already articulated by the language constructs define the expressiveness of that language. The (fundamental) categories of the language apply during modelling as a *commitment*, e.g., a cup of coffee: does the language commit to the distinction between the cup and the coffee? If so, the language has one construct supplying the fundamental principle for \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91liquidness\u8217\'92, and another for \u8216\'91substance you can hold\u8217\'92. Where the former allows arbitrary many subparts of coffee remaining coffee, the latter cannot function as a cup any more when broken. When language does not provide such distinctions, it doesn\u8217\'92t commit to the existence of those different things. Consequently, the user of the language is forced to implement distinctions in the model and create code for that. Whereas domain analysts create models to represent the distinctions that the domain users deem relevant, in philosophy [@Bricker2016] similar questions relate to \u8220\'93life, the universe and everything\u8221\'94 as opposed to a single domain of application. What *kinds* of entities exist? Are the universal aspects that seem to be shared between individual entities, e.g., weight, taken to be *sui generis*? These questions \u8220\'93[\u8230\'85] do not ask for *what there is*, but for what a given remark or doctrine [\u8230\'85] *says* there is\u8221\'94 [@Quine:1953er]. What kinds of entity exist according to a given theory? This is *meta-ontology* and the answers provide a generic framework of distinction that represents a useful meta-model to the domain analyst: the *foundational ontology*, with the articulated distinctions as the language\u8217\'92s *ontological commitment*.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The ontological commitment is relevant for an architecture that deals with semantics as every language, at least implicitly, carries an ontological commitment: Each (linguistic or graphical) language construct will represent something else, and rules constrain how they can be combined. Without considering whether these (implicit) distinctions fit well with the required domain distinctions results in suboptimal semantic accuracy at best, but probably in semantic incoherence: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the opposite of ontology is not non-ontology, but bad ontology\u8221\'94 [@Guizzardi:2015ky, p.260] . Explicitly introducing the ontological commitment of the modelling language is necessary to control the semantic accuracy of the model.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aristotle suggested two orthogonal distinguishing categories: that between }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 types}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  (}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Universals}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ) and }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 individuals}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  (}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Particulars}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ); and that between }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 characteristics}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  (}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Qualities}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  or properties) and their }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 substantials}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  (}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Endurants}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ), with their causal relations, \\cref\{fig:onto-square-and-sextet\}(a). This *ontological square* [@Angelelli1967] can be considered the most basic ontological commitment when acknowledged by a modelling language [@Lowe2006]. Its extension into the ontological sextet [@Smith2005] incorporates time as independent dimension, entailing }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 events}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  (}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Perdurants}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ) (\\cref\{fig:onto-square-and-sextet\}(b)). Similar formal distinctions are observed in contemporary modelling paradigms at their uppermost meta-level: OMG\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s MOF pyramid distinguishes the }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Association}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  from }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Class}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 . All meta-meta-models are intended as generically applicable modelling language. Unfortunately, generality implies that their ontological commitment, their capability to convey differences, is limited. For all examples above, it is impossible to differentiate, for example, between the cup and the coffee, while intuitively, these are not only very different from each other but including these distinctions does not limit its generic applicability as a language. Each foundational ontology has to provide for two principles: Firstly, a *principle of application*, a mechanism to judge whether an individual belongs to a certain type (universal), viz. able to answer questions such as \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is Yojo a cat?\u8221\'94. This is relevant in order to classify individuals, and to understand the characteristics of the *instantiation* relation between types and individuals (\\cref\{fig:onto-square-and-sextet\}). Secondly, a *principle of identity*, a mechanism to make a distinction between two individuals (particulars), which must go beyond provisioning a unique label since such is just a random token. Instead, to answer questions such as \u8220\'93Is Yojo *my* cat?\u8221\'94 requires an identity principle that can *not* be found in the nature of things but for a doctrine that determines the criterion for - here - identity: a social convention about the principle of identity that is applied.  }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
