\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 We equate faithfulness with trueness between the representation and the real entity (\\cref\{fig:semiotic-triangles\}(b)). This aspect is a characteristic of an indirect relationship and can only emerge as a result of the adequacy and correctness edges. Adequacy concerns the quality of the abstraction, which we do not address here. Correctness concerns the quality of the representation. Four construct issues were considered between a conceptualisation and its representation in a model ([@Guizzardi:2005vt;@CarvalhoeSilva2012;@Azevedo2015]). The correctness with which tokens represent the conceptualisation improves when the four construct issues are minimised. The best representation of a conceptualisation is a model that is lucid, sound, laconic and complete, i.e., the subjectivation/representation mapping is isomorphic ([@Guizzardi:2005vt]). This strongly depends on the modelling language, particularly its appropriateness with which it carves-out the reality of the DoI, viz. the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93ontological level\u8221\'94 [@Guarino1994b], our \u8220\'93terminological competence [that] can be gained by formally expressing the ontological commitment of a knowledge base\u8221\'94 (ibid.).}
